In Object-Oriented Programming (OOP), terms like object.method and object.attribute belong to a broader set of
concepts used to organize and protect code. [1, 2, 3]
The Four Pillars of OOP
These are the foundational principles that define how OOP systems should be designed:

* Encapsulation: Bundling data (attributes) and methods that act on that data into a single unit (a class).
It often involves data hiding, where internal details are kept private to protect them from outside misuse.

* Inheritance: A mechanism where a new "child" class (subclass) derives characteristics and behaviors from an
existing "parent" class (superclass). This promotes code reusability.

* Polymorphism: The ability of different objects to respond to the same command (method name) in their own way.
For example, a Dog and a Cat might both have a speak() method, but one barks while the other meows.

* Abstraction: Hiding complex implementation details and showing only the essential features of an object.
This allows users to interact with a simple interface without needing to understand the "under the hood" mechanics.
